%I A393133 #17 Mar 17 2026 16:58:07
%S A393133 1,2,4,21,59,62,77,225,393,478,604,3499,3616,39205,41013,44115,120180,
%T A393133 140309,211937,213599,266973,763017,127891010,145293969,1878902842,
%U A393133 7075483032,9320641829,12471980526,27860075227,29253109979
%N A393133 Iteration numbers k for which MD5^k('') yields record lows.
%C A393133 We consider iterations of the MD5 function which returns a 128-bit hash value as "message digest" for any input sequence of bits. We can feed this result again as input (of length = 128 bit) to the MD5 function.
%C A393133 Here we use the empty string '' as starting value, but list a(1) = 1 as the first record low, corresponding to MD5('') = 0xd41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e.
%C A393133 Thereafter we list "iteration numbers" k such that the k-fold repeated MD5 function yields increasingly lower values.
%C A393133 This is similar to A234849 which lists the k-values for record highs when starting with the empty string, and similar to A393134 which gives the iteration numbers for record lows, starting with a message of 128 bits 1.
%C A393133 The sequence is finite, since the record lows corresponding to the iteration numbers are strictly decreasing to 0, cf. Examples.
%H A393133 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A393133/a393133.txt">Table of n, a(n), record value (in hex), # of leading zeros</a>
%H A393133 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5">MD5</a>.
%e A393133 The following table gives iteration numbers k and the resulting 128 bit message digest in its 32-digit hexadecimal representation, which is fed into the MD5 function at the next iteration:
%e A393133      k | MD5^k('') in hexadecimal         |#lz| record low?
%e A393133   -----+----------------------------------+---+----------------
%e A393133      0 | ""                               | - | no
%e A393133      1 | d41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e | 0 | yes => a(1) = 1
%e A393133      2 | 59adb24ef3cdbe0297f05b395827453f | 1 | yes => a(2) = 2
%e A393133      3 | 8b8154f03b75f58a6c702235bf643629 | 0 | no
%e A393133      4 | 0a314fe6160e361429dd96a2b098126b | 4 | yes => a(3) = 4
%e A393133      5 | b3786b60f640690c03030ebcff4bdf8d | 0 | no
%e A393133    ... | ...                              |...| no
%e A393133     21 | 07598b687b0613b109a1f54abff4800b | 5 | yes => a(4) = 21
%e A393133     59 | 05d645dc6fb19ab372419611795b8b45 | 5 | yes => a(5) = 59
%e A393133     62 | 03cf36e12b2fbdf4909f79791a536532 | 6 | yes => a(6) = 62
%e A393133     77 | 011f3916ecc7bd1dbb3e0373bb660a07 | 7 | yes => a(7) = 77
%e A393133    225 | 00ab4e5809b5d59ea6a2d5e029286956 | 8 | yes => a(8) = 225
%e A393133    393 | 0096e56c187563d2509cf015f8fd39a6 | 8 | yes => a(9) = 393
%e A393133    478 | 007aad42a2209f0b8d35d6d393ac0802 | 9 | yes => a(10) = 478
%e A393133    604 | 00339d9ed22867d3504730be404620bf |10 | yes => a(11) = 604
%e A393133   3499 | 0021c64cee10be8b9db0779154e7c70e |10 | yes => a(12) = 3499
%e A393133    ... | ...                              |...| ...
%e A393133 The number of leading 0-bits (given in column "#lz") in the record values is 0, 1, 4, 5, 5, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 10, 10, 13, 13, 13, 14, 15, 15, 16, 18, 19, 26, ....
%o A393133 (Python)
%o A393133 from hashlib import md5
%o A393133 def A393133_gen():
%o A393133     msg = u''; record = b'\xff' # > md5('') = 0xd4...
%o A393133     for i in range(1,1<<63): # sys.maxint: practically infinity
%o A393133         msg = md5(msg).digest()
%o A393133         if msg < record: record = msg; yield i; #print(i, msg.hex())
%o A393133 print([an for an,i in zip(A393134_gen(),range(16))])
%Y A393133 Cf. A393134: iteration numbers for record lows when starting with 128 bits 1.
%Y A393133 Cf. A234849, A393294: iteration numbers for record highs when starting with 0 resp. 128 bits 0.
%K A393133 nonn,hard,more,fini
%O A393133 1,2
